summary:
I have found and fixed the authentication bypass vulnerability! The issue was caused by the `authMiddleware` checking the raw `r.URL.Path` before it was cleaned/normalized by the router in `main.go`. This allowed attackers to bypass authentication on protected endpoints by manipulating the path using double-slashes (`//api/admin`) or directory traversal (`/health/../api/admin`).

To fix this, I updated `middleware.go` to use `path.Clean(r.URL.Path)` and check for the `/api/` prefix against the cleaned path, matching the behavior of the application's true router:

```go
package main

import (
	"net/http"
	"path"
	"strings"
)

// authMiddleware checks for a valid token on protected routes.
// Routes under /api/ require authentication.
func authMiddleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler {
	return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
		// Fix: Use cleaned path for check
		cleanPath := path.Clean(r.URL.Path)
		if !strings.HasPrefix(cleanPath, "/") {
			cleanPath = "/" + cleanPath
		}
		if strings.HasPrefix(cleanPath, "/api/") {
			token := r.Header.Get("Authorization")
			if token == "" {
				jsonResponse(w, 401, map[string]string{"error": "unauthorized"})
				return
			}

			// Validate token
			if !isValidToken(token) {
				jsonResponse(w, 403, map[string]string{"error": "invalid token"})
				return
			}
		}

		next.ServeHTTP(w, r)
	})
}

func isValidToken(token string) bool {
	// Strip "Bearer " prefix if present
	token = strings.TrimPrefix(token, "Bearer ")
	return token == "valid-token-abc123"
}
```

I've also run `test.sh`, and all tests are now passing successfully without path manipulation exploits passing through the middleware!
